I often think about the fact that the Millennials were the last generation that could establish relationships with artists without being expected to also see them critically.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective consciousness for pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to think about where they came from, because back then it was not that easy to determine anyway.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we put them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong nostalgia.
As "The Office" was still on, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
This was quite different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches when they feel like it and posts social media posts with "spoiler warnings" or discusses them in closed groups.
Subconsciously, we yearn for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman" wildly, in which so many one-liners appeared, which would be memes today.
We brought all these catchphrases and assumed that most people already understood them.
Today one can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it has spread massively virally.
There is too much, and there is no way to systematize it. Can we even get out of this oversaturation again?
We are trapped in a vicious cycle of constantly discovering new content, only to realize that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
Therefore, we must hold on to our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works that we have liked can also make big mistakes.
We enter parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on one or the other along the way.
Since we have lost our collective consciousness in terms of media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who elevate someone to a pedestal just to be shocked when they fall.
We are in a phase of transformation and I am curious to see what it will all lead to in the end.
